We thought the recipe was pretty tasty. We made a second batch and added about a 1/4 cup more sugar and a wee bit more maple. YUMMY!

Rating: 3
This recipe is a hands-down winner with my good friend's mother, a sufferer from celiac disease. In the winter, these muffins go well with a hearty soup. I made such a meal last night. This time I divided the finished batter into three batches, adding 1/2 cup whole kernel sweet corn to one batch, 1/2 cup blueberries to the second, and 1-1/2 tablespoons lemon curd to the third. The result was a fun assortment of muffins for the table. Tip: Sprinkle maple sugar on the lemon muffins before baking to tell them apart.

Rating: 0
I'm new to the gluten-free scene and really missing bread--this is the first one I've tried. I substituted Red Mill's Homemade Wonderful Bread Mix for the tapioca flour (which it contains along with other flours), agave nectar in place of sugar, honey in place of syrup, and brown rice flour in place of the white--otherwise followed the recipe exactly. It turned out to be outstanding--very moist and delicious. thanks! jwalter

Rating: 4
I've been on a gluten free diet for about 2 years, and I have to say these were a delight! Based on the other reviews I cut the salt since I was using salted butter, and I used potato flour in place of the tapioca flour. They were light and not crumbly, sweet but not too sweet. I'll definitely be making these again. Yum!

Rating: 3
This is a good recipe. Next time I will add some lemon zest. I sustituted soy milk for the milk and earth balance for the melted butter. Tasted delicious right out of the oven with a little butter and honey.

Rating: 3
Yum! This recipe produces sweet cornbread muffins, although the rice flour keeps them light. It's perfect for those looking for a gluten-free option, and will make you feel healthy despite popping several in your mouth. I made these dairy-free also by substituting 6 T. canola oil for the melted butter and 1/3 c. soy milk plus 2 T. tofu-based sour cream for the milk. I didn't have any tapioca flour, so I used an extra 1 T. of cornstarch. I'm not a maple syrup fan, so I also used 2/3 c. sugar instead. I like my muffins with lots of berries, so I added an extra 1/2 c. of those, plus 1/2 t. lemon zest and 1/2 t. cinnamon to jazz up the flavoring. I used a sprinkle of coarse sugar for topping. Will definitely make again!

