Make this muffin and you will be so happy!

Rating: 3
I have been experimenting with gluten free muffin recipes lately...for a friend who was recently diagnosed with a gluten intolerance.... These muffins were good: flavor, texture. I agree with some other reviewers that they are a little salty, but perhaps that is because I used salted butter - that is all I had on hand. I omitted the tapioca flour because I did not have it, and they still turned out tasty. I also used MORE than 1 cup of fresh blueberries.

Rating: 3
Followed the recipe exactly, but I used a blend of berries and some dried currants. It turned out a lot like a berry-filled cornbread. A little on the dry side, but add some butter and/or honey and it's a lovely GF recipe. It was a tiny bit sweet for me. If you want it to be more like a cornbread muffin, you could probably use less maple syrup, or try using something less sweet, like apple sauce or date sugar.

Rating: 4
I find this the most moist and flavourful gluten free muffin I've found. I add the zest and juice from one lemon to make them more flavourful. I've also used this recipe as a base for carrot muffins as well - and it works amazing.

Rating: 2
I would have given this a one forker. However, I did have to use Ener-g egg replacer for the eggs, and I used almond milk instead of whole milk (which would greatly change texture). The muffins came out really crumbly and I think I can taste some of the baking powder or corn starch in there. This is one of the first smattering of gluten free recipes I've tried. It uses a lot of corn starch, maybe others use as much, but that's the most I've ever put into one recipe.

Rating: 3
Before I knew I had to stop eating wheat I made several blueberry corn muffin recipes. This recipe was every bit as good as any I've tried. Mine were not dry at all or dense. I followed the recipe exactly, I'm not sure why others had problems. I will definitely make them again. I think next time I will add some lemon zest to the batter.

Rating: 3
I just made this recipe for a friend who has a wheat allergy. They are beautiful-looking and quite tasty. They're not fluffy like blueberry muffins but are more like a nice, sweet cornbread. I used both blueberries and raspberries, which added a nice, tart flavor. I also used a little more sugar than the recipe called for.

